Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Wednesday! Apologies for getting this one out a day late =E2=80=94 I =
was a little under the weather but back at it and feeling good.=20
Every week in the Weekly Dose of Optimism, we highlight five stories of the=
 incredible things that humans pull off. The Weekly Dose started as a small=
 fight back against the prevailing sense of pessimism in the air that I des=
cribed in Optimism [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/bbd9aa57-7e3d-4ecb-bf=
4c-023daee98e9a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ].
Recently, though, Dan and I have noticed the winds shifting. There=E2=80=99=
s a growing sense of optimism beyond this little newsletter. We are so back=
=2E=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
WTF Happened in 2023?
When economic historians in 2073 look back on the past fifty years of growt=
h and abundance, they=E2=80=99ll pull up a bunch of charts, and one questio=
n will jump out at them: WTF Happened In 2023?
Maybe I=E2=80=99m drunk on a cocktail of optimism and technological progres=
s, but it feels like 2023 is the turning point: from Stagnation to Accelera=
tion.
The last big turning point is clear in hindsight, so clear that there=E2=80=
=99s a whole website dedicated to a single year: WTF Happened in 1971? [ ht=
tps://link.sbstck.com/redirect/9d8a01e7-f609-4ef8-9917-2786ccf2429a?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s just dozens of graphs showing that things kept getting more aw=
esome until 1971 and then stopped getting more awesome after 1971.=C2=A0
Economist Tyler Cowen calls the period since 1971 The Great Stagnation [ ht=
tps://link.sbstck.com/redirect/88c6c20b-5a8e-495f-8f83-cc8127da9861?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a half-centu=
ry slowdown in productivity and innovation.=C2=A0
It wouldn=E2=80=99t have been obvious in 1971 that things were going to slo=
w so dramatically. The data might have looked a little wobbly, but that hap=
pens year to year. There might have been clues, though, if you were looking=
: the dollar depegged from gold, regulation was increasing, America was los=
ing in Vietnam, growth fell out of vogue. You might have picked up a shift =
from optimism to pessimism, which trickled into policies, corporate decisio=
ns, and then, years later, into the data.=C2=A0
I think we=E2=80=99re at a similar but opposite point in 2023. We won=E2=80=
=99t be able to see it in the data for a while, but you can already feel it=
 in the air. It=E2=80=99s just wisps, and I=E2=80=99m admittedly cherry-pic=
king, but the wisps are everywhere.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re shifting from indefinite pessimism and insanity to what I'll =
call pragmatic optimism - a balanced, realistic optimism focused on achieva=
ble progress. Over the past 18 months, prevailing sentiment became irration=
ally pessimistic based on how bad we heard everything was, and turned pragm=
atically optimistic based on our lived experience that it wasn=E2=80=99t. S=
ocial media amplified and spotlighted extreme views, and after the violent =
amplification of extreme views on both ends, we=E2=80=99re settling somewhe=
re more sane. Reality is winning, and reality is pretty good, actually.=C2=
=A0
At the same time, we=E2=80=99re in a period of technological acceleration. =
We talk about it all the time here: AI finally works, the economics of spac=
e pencil out, fusion startups are making progress, renewable energy is boom=
ing, and now we might even get room-temperature superconductors. Optimism s=
hapes reality, and an optimistic foundation is necessary to leverage instea=
d of impede the benefits of these technologies.=C2=A0
In short: it=E2=80=99s a perfect storm of sentiment shift and technological=
 progress that could mark the end of The Great Stagnation and the beginning=
 of The Great Acceleration.=C2=A0
I know, I know, when you have a hammer, everything looks like a nail. Last =
summer, in Optimism [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/bbd9aa57-7e3d-4ecb-b=
f4c-023daee98e9a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ], I argued that:=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re more pessimistic than we should be.
Optimism shapes reality.
The downside to optimism is limited, the upside is uncapped.
So of course I would overindex on optimism as the kindling for The Great Ac=
celeration. But I really do think optimism is a necessary precondition, and=
 there are signs that pragmatic optimism is both back and shaping reality. =
I=E2=80=99ll give five examples:=C2=A0
The Dimon Speech
Consumer Sentiment and the Economy
Infrastructure and Manufacturing
Nuclear Energy
Superconductors
They=E2=80=99re just wisps at this point, but taken together, they begin to=
 paint a picture.=C2=A0
The Dimon Speech
The first time my Spidey Sense really started to tingle was when, right aro=
und the 4th of July this year, a video of JP Morgan CEO Jamie Dimon speakin=
g at The Economic Club went viral [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/f88cb3=
59-09de-4e8b-b4bd-9c95d3d55afa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
Dimon=E2=80=99s was the most unabashedly optimistic message about America=
=E2=80=99s position from any major leader in a long time, the antithesis of=
 that Jeff Daniels rant against American Exceptionalism in the opening epis=
ode of Newsroom [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/5154e790-dffd-475e-a959-=
b8267275d5f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ]. People cheered the message, and called for a Dimon 2024 Presidentia=
l run.=C2=A0
He might run, no idea, although it seems unlikely this late in the game. Bu=
t one thing is for certain: this video was not part of a 2024 Presidential =
campaign. This video was from 2016.=C2=A0
That people received a patriotically optimistic rant from a Big Bank CEO en=
thusiastically was telling on its own, but the fact that the video floated =
around the internet ether for seven years until people were ready for it is=
 fascinating. In 2016, Americans wanted to Make America Great Again; in 202=
3, they celebrated the fact that, despite its issues, it=E2=80=99s already =
pretty great.=C2=A0
One reason we may have been more receptive to that message in 2023 is that,=
 in the face of what we were told would be a brutal recession, the American=
 economy stood strong.=C2=A0
Consumer Sentiment and the Economy
Pessimists and extremists overplayed their hands during periods of uncertai=
nty and are being exposed; now optimism and sanity are taking root.=C2=A0
To be fair, permabulls like me got too excited during the COVID bull run, w=
hich invited macro bears to gleefully predict that the world was going to f=
all apart once the Fed started raising rates. Consumer sentiment sank to an=
 all-time low of 50 last June as people bought into the doom.=C2=A0
And then=E2=80=A6 the economy didn=E2=80=99t fall apart. It=E2=80=99s doing=
 pretty great, actually, as Noah Smith laid out on Monday [ https://link.sb=
stck.com/redirect/021ac649-1ec3-463d-9bac-df8aadce7ca8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Real GDP growth hit 2.4%.=
 Inflation cooled to 3%. Age-adjusted employment is the best it=E2=80=99s e=
ver been.=C2=A0
As a result, consumer sentiment rebounded sharply to 71.6 in July, marking =
the fastest growth in sentiment since 1984 at 39%.=C2=A0
In absolute terms, 71.6 is still low, well below the 85.6 average over the =
70 year life of the UMich survey, but if we=E2=80=99re looking for shifts i=
n sentiment, that relative improvement is an important signal. People can f=
eel the momentum.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re in no way out of the woods. The data could turn. But as it st=
ands, it=E2=80=99s almost as if we simulated the worst case scenarios virtu=
ally and came back more confident in the real world. On the ground, while t=
here are weaknesses in real estate and household wealth, and while a recess=
ion may still hit, right now jobs are plentiful, wages are growing, inflati=
on is cooling, inequality is shrinking, and manufacturing is booming.=C2=A0
Infrastructure and Manufacturing
Speaking of building things=E2=80=A6 one of the biggest knocks against Amer=
ica is that we=E2=80=99ve forgotten how to build big things fast. That=E2=
=80=99s a well-deserved criticism and both a symptom and cause of our stagn=
ation. As I wrote in How to Fix a Country in 12 Days [ https://link.sbstck.=
com/redirect/28cc3f14-1a8c-426a-9663-55f6aa1c9cd8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CAmericans built the E=
mpire State Building in just 410 days; NYC=E2=80=99s Second Avenue Subway p=
roject, California=E2=80=99s High-Speed Rail, and Boston=E2=80=99s Big Dig =
have missed their timelines by decades and their budgets by tens of billion=
s of dollars.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
But that same piece highlighted a tiny glimmer of hope: the I-95 Rebuild. F=
or 12 days, people were captivated by Philadelphia=E2=80=99s effort to rebu=
ild a damaged stretch of highway as quickly as possible.=C2=A0
Look, it was just a temporary fix to a piece of road less than half-a-footb=
all-field long. It=E2=80=99s easy to imagine a version of the world in whic=
h the project was met with bemused cynicism, but people were just genuinely=
 enthused. Americans want to live in a country that builds things again.=C2=
=A0=C2=A0
On its own, it was a fun diversion, but the I-95 rebuild came against the b=
ackdrop of a country that=E2=80=99s trying to prove to itself that it can b=
uild again. Construction spending on manufacturing has shot up to record hi=
ghs this year, spurred by the CHIPs Act and Inflation Reduction Act.=C2=A0
The building debate seems to have moved from a high-level battle over wheth=
er we can or should build big things again into the nitty gritty details: p=
ermitting reform, job training, immigration.=C2=A0
This is what I mean by pragmatic optimism: excitement coupled with a focus =
on the specific challenges we need to overcome to build the future that we =
want.=C2=A0
Nuclear Energy=C2=A0
In nuclear energy, too, the conversation is shifting to focus on specific c=
hallenges to tackle. Nuclear=E2=80=99s resurgence signals two healthy thing=
s:=C2=A0
Recognition that more energy is good, contested during the Great Stagnation=
=2E=C2=A0=C2=A0
Fact-based instead of ideological analysis of where to get that energy.=C2=
=A0
Certainly, the War in Ukraine played a role in bringing sanity back into th=
e conversation. Germany=E2=80=99s hypocrisy =E2=80=93 favoring Russian gas =
and dirty coal to clean, abundant nuclear =E2=80=93 forced people to reexam=
ine their assumptions. When they did, nuclear came out looking good.=C2=A0
In a recent Pew poll [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/bbdff4b5-4724-4309-=
8308-fab475de0df9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], nuclear power was the only energy source that saw growing supp=
ort from both Democrats and Republicans.=C2=A0
Now, while there=E2=80=99s still work to be done to counter the damaging ef=
fects of the anti-nuclear disinformation campaign that persisted throughout=
 The Great Stagnation, the most pressing challenges are more practical: we =
want more nuclear power, but it=E2=80=99s too slow and expensive right now.=
=C2=A0
Yesterday, Georgia=E2=80=99s Vogle Unit 3 reactor [ https://link.sbstck.com=
/redirect/c286751c-4fc6-488e-862a-0953d697625f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the first newly constructed nucle=
ar unit in the US in over 30 years, began commercial operation. That=E2=80=
=99s a huge win, but it also highlights the need to get faster and cheaper.=
 It arrived seven years late and $17 billion over budget.=C2=A0
The future of nuclear power rests on the practical instead of the ideologic=
al. How can we untangle the messy web of regulation, financing, and constru=
ction to build new nuclear capacity quickly and cheaply? What role can smal=
l modular reactors and other advanced reactor designs play? These are quest=
ions that a pragmatically optimistic society can tackle.=C2=A0
Superconductors
Then, of course, there are the superconductors, which are simultaneously a =
product of the pragmatic optimism (the Race to Replicate) and, if replicate=
d, a driver of pragmatic optimism (how can we manufacture LK-99 at scale an=
d what can we build with it?).
If LK-99 is legit and we can manufacture it at scale (big ifs!), it does se=
em to be the kind of technological breakthrough that could unleash a Great =
Acceleration. This thread [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/ed49c0b6-4ecb-=
4e14-a160-1177fd86a734?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has 500 replies with the things people are =E2=80=9Cmost s=
toked for if LK-99 turns out to be a room temp superconductor.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
The prediction market Manifold [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/4baaa71d-=
4dec-4636-9dc4-5a222b643232?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] currently puts the odds of replication at 34%, but wh=
ether or not it replicates, the pragmatic optimism on display has been phen=
omenal.=C2=A0
I think this superconductor experience is something that could only happen =
in the current environment: pragmatic optimists connected across the globe =
watching science experiments like sports and getting really excited but wai=
ting for a bunch of national and academic labs and assorted internet genius=
es [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/181df528-145d-4f29-8123-28d02f896edc?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to rep=
licate before getting too excited. As Amjad put it [ https://link.sbstck.co=
m/redirect/0f2be598-2908-40a8-85c8-b5e87d5bf0f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve had a version of this piece in my drafts for a month, long bef=
ore I=E2=80=99d ever heard the words =E2=80=9Croom-temperature superconduct=
or=E2=80=9D strung together. Instead of the prime mover of backness, it fee=
ls like the Race to Replicate is a confirmation that things really are shif=
ting.=C2=A0
Again, it=E2=80=99s just a wisp. But against the drumbeat of declining trus=
t in institutions, it=E2=80=99s beautiful to see people around the world sa=
y, =E2=80=9CFuck it. We=E2=80=99ll do it ourselves.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Growth is back on, but The Great Acceleration will be a different flavor th=
an pre-1971 growth.=C2=A0
The Gains from Truly Mobilizing the Internet
In a 2020 follow-up to his Great Stagnation book, Tyler Cowen wrote a blog =
titled What might an end to the Great Stagnation consist of? [ https://link=
=2Esbstck.com/redirect/78de5efe-bbff-4=
eda-ba84-df98c4c8c57d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. He concluded with this=
 observation: =E2=80=9CThe gains from truly mobilizing the internet may in =
fact right now be swamping all of the accumulated obstacles we have put in =
the way of progress.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not sure if this is how he meant it, but I think the internet h=
as played a crucial role in reigniting optimism, even if the path there was=
 a bit painful. It amplified the craziest views, and I think we=E2=80=99re =
starting to realize that most of us are happier somewhere in the middle. It=
 helped spread doom and gloom, forcing a confrontation with reality that re=
ality is starting to win. It touches each of the wisps I covered in this es=
say, in direct or indirect ways. And it made the global race to replicate a=
 non-peer reviewed paper both possible in the first place and a captivating=
 live event.=C2=A0
The internet also enables a healthy self-policing optimism =E2=80=93 the hi=
ve mind swarms overly grandiose or underly specific claims. It=E2=80=99s wo=
rth highlighting your own obstacles and inviting others to help solve them =
before the internet identifies them for you and labels you a fraud.=C2=A0
In Working Harder and Smarter [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/72adc829-3=
67b-428e-aeec-cb46d91a727b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I argued that the last fifty years, spent developing =
software and services at the expense of Total Factor Productivity, weren=E2=
=80=99t a period of stagnation at all, but a necessary precondition for the=
 accelerated progress we can make when we combine innovation in bits and at=
oms. A year later, we=E2=80=99re starting to see signs that that may be tru=
e.=C2=A0
After decades of dealing with the instability of a shift from centralizatio=
n to decentralization, it feels like we=E2=80=99re settling into a more sta=
bly decentralized world [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/3f2d8792-750a-43=
aa-8b9d-4604bb1db06f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Instead of waiting for peer review, people are replicating =
themselves. Instead of slowly pushing infrastructure projects through burea=
ucracy, politicians are rallying support online. Instead of relying on pote=
ntially hostile enemies for energy and manufacturing, countries are buildin=
g capabilities at home.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
My evidence is just wisps and hints. A more fact-based argument could be ma=
de that we are not so back, that it really is so over. The superconductor m=
ight not replicate; current odds are that it won=E2=80=99t. AI could be reg=
ulated to death or cause real harm. A recession may still come. Polarizatio=
n is still a thing. Governments and institutions are slow to shift, even wh=
en people want them to.=C2=A0 Progress could increase inequality and lower =
happiness, since we so often measure happiness on a relative basis.=C2=A0
In fact, there=E2=80=99s a good chance that if you polled people today, mos=
t of them would think that I=E2=80=99m crazy for suggesting that optimism i=
s on the rise. Maybe my brain=E2=80=99s been warped by the internet, or the=
 X algo has just gotten really good at showing me what I want to see.=C2=A0
My hunch, though, is that things look particularly bleak before the shift, =
just like things looked particularly rosy in 1970. Those wisps and many tha=
t we haven=E2=80=99t covered, advances in biotech, education, space, defens=
e =E2=80=93 we didn=E2=80=99t even talk about AI! =E2=80=93 are early clues=
 that things are shifting. Maybe you feel it.=C2=A0
The Great Acceleration is not inevitable. Cruft built up over the last fift=
y years of stagnation threatens to jam the gears of progress. Regulations a=
re harder to tear down than they are to build up. We=E2=80=99re already fac=
ing a shortage of skilled laborers needed to build the things we=E2=80=99re=
 building now =E2=80=93 like chips and houses =E2=80=93 and we=E2=80=99re g=
oing to need a lot more: nuclear engineers, machinists, materials scientist=
s, craftspeople. We need politicians who reflect the vigor and drive of the=
 people. We need to demand excellence of ourselves.=C2=A0
There are a million details to tackle, but I think we have the momentum to =
tackle them.
If we get it right, future generations will look back admiringly and ask, W=
TF Happened In 2023? =C2=A0
Thanks to Dan [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/587789d6-0ddc-4827-bf36-b1=
7df4c4067c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with the Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

